<subSubSection id="8A916201D81ACAD0E221AD7D8D52142E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type species">
<paragraph id="8D9C7EE69A2EDE8AA40198174A2716B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="01484EB72D8FC6E6B9A591E11865AA05" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="DD63E4D9DE4665ECDE5F780CFCD6818D" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Stereocaulaceae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xyleborus emarginatus" order="Lecanorales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="emarginatus">
<emphasis id="23E86750E7D1F98C6BC19C5DB4B7711F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xyleborus emarginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Eichhoff, 1878; original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5BFE8932C78B3F758104D0956669D4EA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D056413B8D6B943486CCA8E0B2D336D3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B08D84D7A49556E49742EC826E4478C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
2.2-5.4 mm, 2.68-3.85
<normalizedToken id="2B4C9275A228CFFEF0738D26C4A24C78" originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide. 
<taxonomicName id="E422D29089B2602BEACB356B8A8498AA" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2010" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Debus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Debus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="88F96396A04137E3710294EBEF856745" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Debus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the pronotal disc flat and elongate, pronotum from dorsal view long, rounded frontally (type 9, rarely type 7); elytral apex emarginate (except 
<taxonomicName id="FFA0FAF1FCA39588C49840B9ECD295D4" genus="D." lsidName="D. adusticollis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="adusticollis">
<emphasis id="1E4B5F7320C2438AC39DABE3339A01F0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. adusticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in our region); elytra typically strongly excavated and explanate; first declivital interstriae broadened, laterally displacing strial punctures; protibiae distinctly triangular with fewer than six large denticles on lateral margin. In addition, mycangial tufts are absent, procoxae are contiguous and scutellum flat and flush with the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B44B9FAD6EA67D4233E76E4A87A2DAD1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="similar genera">
<paragraph id="323C40C3B14A035662219746D601B958" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Similar genera.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="52F540EFE79854E79259ED4FACA2457F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="5E734ADBDA6764D2BD587D7E6B43C924" authorityName="Schedl" authorityYear="1939" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Streptocranus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Streptocranus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1026594DD1F317E3212F74CE1A95C515" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Streptocranus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="85DFB1396C6972D471CE73AD713DD9D4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="665A57344E83DAC970BD6387A6A6CBE4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C749842ED400A4B9CA993799177C9BCC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Common in tropical forests throughout South Asia to the far reaches of the Pacific Ocean.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DAADC650BE063587A7F49E3F342BC856" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="gallery system">
<paragraph id="F4F2D4615C12B25553047F5D8BF792D1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Gallery system.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="141AC3144C2909BC087F9F2B8A089AF3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This usually has a transverse surface gallery between the bark and wood, part of which is expanded by the larvae into a brood chamber in which many of them develop. Further branching tunnels penetrate directly into the wood. These too develop brood chambers in the longitudinal plane. Brood development proceeds normally in the wood, if the tree is debarked. In some species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="2728276F2020736912F81D8ACB0E0CB8" genus="D." lsidName="D. adusticollis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="adusticollis">
<emphasis id="42CE341C7367FFAFE1B8830E61AE26E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. adusticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), surface galleries and brood chambers have not been observed (
<bibRefCitation id="8A49ACCAB5AAE41A0B160FB968D954F1" author="Kalshoven, LGE" journalOrPublisher="Tijdschrift voor Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="135 - 173" refId="B220" refString="Kalshoven, LGE, 1959b. Studies on the biology of Indonesian Scolytoidea 4. Data on the habits of Scolytidae. Second part. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 102: 135 - 173" title="Studies on the biology of Indonesian Scolytoidea 4. Data on the habits of Scolytidae. Second part." volume="102" year="1959 b">Kalshoven 1959b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="3403EC211449E0E272CBA8E9CFA9F791" author="Browne, FG" journalOrPublisher="Malayan Forest Records" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 255" refId="B70" refString="Browne, FG, 1961b. The biology of Malayan Scolytidae and Platypodidae. Malayan Forest Records 22: 1 - 255" title="The biology of Malayan Scolytidae and Platypodidae." volume="22" year="1961 b">Browne 1961b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
